@flexiarg aif/two-layer-calibration
@title Two-Layer Calibration (Dynamics-Consistency vs Witnessed-Outcome)
@sigils [L1/L2]
@keywords calibration, prior-equals-value, dynamics, value, witnessed outcome, three-witness, self-reference, G-vs-G, reward gating
@audience anyone calibrating a value/forward model against a field the model helps compose
@tone architectural
@style pattern

! conclusion: When you calibrate a model whose own outputs compose the field it is scored against, split the calibration into TWO layers and never let one stand in for the other. L1 — dynamics/consistency (does the field respond to measured state?): cheap, accrues every cycle, and is NEVER value evidence. L2 — outcome-vs-prediction (did real functioning result?): scarce, witnessed, gated, and is the ONLY value clearance.

  + context: You are calibrating a forward/value model against a live field, and the field's value
    function is computed from the same effects the model predicts with (`prior == value` risk).

  + IF:
      Predicted-vs-realised pairs are your evidence that the model is "calibrated".

  + HOWEVER:
      On such a field the comparison is largely self-referential: it tests dynamics-consistency
      (did the world move as the model's state-response said?), NOT whether the model's VALUE is
      right — because the realised IS the model's own output. A model can pass this layer forever
      while being worthless at predicting real outcomes. Worse, fixing the obvious circularity
      (making predict-effects state-sensitive) RELOCATES it rather than removing it: state-blindness
      breaks, but the error *magnitude* stays model-priced.

  + THEN:
      Name and keep both layers explicitly. **L1 = G-vs-G dynamics**: cheap, every cycle, labelled
      never-value-evidence; it earns its keep as a consistency/sanity layer. **L2 =
      outcome-vs-prediction** against WITNESSED outcomes the model did not produce — closure-folds,
      three-witness certificates, attested real functioning — scarce, gated behind the reward
      discipline. Only L2 clears value. Forbid L1's cheap pass from being reported as L2 clearance.

  + BECAUSE:
      The only thing that escapes `prior == value` is a referent the model had no hand in. L1's
      referent (the field) is the model's own output, so L1 can only ever measure internal
      consistency. L2's referent (a witnessed outcome) is external, so it is the only layer that can
      be WRONG about value — which is exactly why it is the gate, not an enhancement.

  + canonical-instance:
      FutonZero G-SIM (WM-pilot, 2026-06-11): L1 dynamics live — the state-sensitive model is 2.55×
      better than the constant counterfactual at predicting no-move — while L2 stays gated behind
      pudding-G1's binding of the arrow-witness to witnessed affect/outcome. The split was forced by
      discovering the calibration was self-certifying (`[[aif/no-self-certification]]`).
